How @Transactional Works Internally (REAL AOP):
  High-Level Flow:
      Client
        ↓
      Proxy (TransactionInterceptor)
        ↓
      Start Transaction
        ↓
      Business Method
        ↓
      Commit / Rollback
🔹 Step-by-Step Internal Working:
      Step 1: Annotation Detection - Spring scans:
            @Transactional
            public void transfer() {}
      Step 2: Proxy Creation - Spring wraps bean with proxy containing:  TransactionInterceptor
      Step 3: Method Call Intercepted-   When method is called:  proxy.transfer()
      Step 4: Transaction Starts-  Internally: transactionManager.begin();
      Step 5: Execute Business Logic -  target.transfer();
      Step 6: Commit or Rollback
              if (success) {
                  commit();
              } else {
                  rollback();
              }
Real Internal Classes (Advanced):
      TransactionInterceptor
      PlatformTransactionManager
      TransactionAspectSupport
Simplified Internal Code:
      public Object invoke(MethodInvocation invocation) throws Throwable {
          TransactionStatus status = txManager.getTransaction();
          try {
              Object result = invocation.proceed(); // actual method
              txManager.commit(status);
              return result;
          } catch (Exception e) {
              txManager.rollback(status);
              throw e;
          }
      }

1: Difference between JoinPoint and ProceedingJoinPoint?
      JoinPoint      	ProceedingJoinPoint
      Read-only	      Can control execution
      All advice	    Only @Around
2: Why Spring AOP supports only method execution?
      Because:
      It uses proxy pattern
      Not bytecode weaving (like AspectJ)
3: Can we modify method arguments?-> ✅ Only with ProceedingJoinPoint ; pjp.proceed(newArgs);
4: Does AOP work on static methods? 👉 ❌ No
5: What happens if multiple aspects match same join point? 👉 All will execute based on @Order
6: What is weaving?
    Process of applying aspects:
        Compile-time (AspectJ)
        Load-time
        Runtime (Spring AOP)


Spring Testing:
    Spring provides powerful testing support using:
        JUnit 5
        Mockito
        Spring Test Context Framework

Types of Testing in Spring:
  1. Unit Testing:
          Test individual classes
          Use Mockito
          @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
          class UserServiceTest {
              @Mock
              UserRepository repo;
              @InjectMocks
              UserService service;
              @Test
              void testFindUser() {
                  when(repo.findById(1)).thenReturn(Optional.of(new User()));
                  User user = service.getUser(1);
                  assertNotNull(user);
              }
          }
  2. Integration Testing:
          Load Spring context
          Test real beans
          @SpringBootTest
          class UserServiceIntegrationTest {
              @Autowired
              UserService service;
              @Test
              void testService() {
                  assertNotNull(service);
              }
          }
  3. Web Layer Testing:
        @WebMvcTest(UserController.class)
        class UserControllerTest {
            @Autowired
            MockMvc mockMvc;
            @MockBean
            UserService service;
            @Test
            void testAPI() throws Exception {
                mockMvc.perform(get("/users"))
                       .andExpect(status().isOk());
            }
        }
Important Annotations:
      Annotation	        Purpose
      @SpringBootTest	    Full application context
      @WebMvcTest	        Controller layer
      @DataJpaTest	      JPA layer
      @MockBean	          Mock Spring bean
      @Autowired	        Inject dependency
      @ExtendWith	        Integrate JUnit

MockMvc (API Testing Without Server):
      No need to start Tomcat
      Fast testing
          mockMvc.perform(post("/users")
                  .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
                  .content("{\"name\":\"John\"}"))
                  .andExpect(status().isCreated());

 Best Practices:
      Prefer unit tests for logic
      Use integration tests sparingly (slow)
      Mock external dependencies
      Use Testcontainers for DB testing (advanced)

