2. Mockito (Mocking Framework):
    Mock dependencies (fake objects) to isolate unit tests
    🔹 Why Mockito?
       Example:  UserService → UserRepository → DB
         We don’t want DB in unit test → mock repository  
    🔹 Basic Example:
        @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
        class UserServiceTest {
            @Mock
            UserRepository repo;
            @InjectMocks
            UserService service;
            @Test
            void testGetUser() {
                when(repo.findById(1)).thenReturn(Optional.of(new User()));
                User user = service.getUser(1);
                assertNotNull(user);
            }
        }
    🔹 Core Annotations:
          Annotation	                          Purpose
          @Mock	                                Create mock object
          @InjectMocks	                        Inject mocks into class
          @Spy	                                Partial mock
          @Captor	                              Capture arguments
          @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)	  Enable Mockito
    🔹 Common Methods:
        1. Stubbing -when(repo.findById(1)).thenReturn(user);
        2. Verify - verify(repo).findById(1);
        3. Argument Matchers -  when(repo.findById(anyInt())).thenReturn(user);
        4. Exception Testing - when(repo.save(any())).thenThrow(new RuntimeException());
    
    🔹 @Spy (Partial Mock):
          @Spy
          List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
          @Test
          void testSpy() {
              list.add("A");
              verify(list).add("A");
          }
    🔹 ArgumentCaptor:
          @Captor
          ArgumentCaptor<User> captor;
          verify(repo).save(captor.capture());
          User saved = captor.getValue();

 3. PowerMockito (Advanced Mocking):
     PowerMockito is used when Mockito cannot handle:
    🔹 Why PowerMockito?
         Mockito CANNOT mock:
            static methods ❌
            final classes ❌ (older versions)
            private methods ❌
            constructors ❌
        PowerMockito solves this
    🔹 Example: Static Method Mock
            @RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
            @PrepareForTest(Utility.class)
            public class TestClass {
                @Test
                public void testStatic() {
                    PowerMockito.mockStatic(Utility.class);
                    when(Utility.getValue()).thenReturn("Mocked");
                    assertEquals("Mocked", Utility.getValue());
                }
            }
    🔹 Example: Constructor Mock
              PowerMockito.whenNew(User.class)
                  .withAnyArguments()
                  .thenReturn(mockUser);
    🔹 Example: Private Method Mock
          PowerMockito.spy(service);
          PowerMockito.doReturn("mock")
              .when(service, "privateMethod");
    Important Note:
       PowerMockito is mostly deprecated / discouraged now
       Modern alternative:  Mockito 3+ supports static mocking:
            try (MockedStatic<Utility> mocked = mockStatic(Utility.class)) {
                mocked.when(Utility::getValue).thenReturn("Mock");
            }

